{
  "doc_id": "26008",
  "text": "To date, no clinical test is reliable enough on its own to support a diagnosis of active alcohol dependence or abuse in the general population. Indeed, traditional blood biomarker tests for detecting alcohol use have not been universally accepted or generally adopted in clinical practice because of their low accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity [CITATION_1] , as they are influenced by several factors including age, gender, and also on the population being studied . Combining two or more tests has been shown to improve predictive values for determining recent heavy use [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , indicating that monitoring more than a single marker may be critical as has been reported for cancer [CITATION_4] .",
